===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|dormous|lang=enm}}, of uncertain origin. Possibly from {{term||dor-|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|non|en}} {{term|dár||benumbed|lang=non}} + {{term|mous||mouse|lang=enm}}. More at {{l/en|doze}}, {{l/en|mouse}}. <br>Although the word has come to be associated as an {{etyl|xno|-}} derivative of  {{etyl|fro|-}} {{term|dormir||to sleep|lang=fro}}, no such Anglo-Norman word is known to have existed <ref>Random House Dictionary, dormouse.</ref>.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|/ˈdɔɹmaʊs/}}
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈdɔːmaʊs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|dormice}}

# Any of several species of small, mostly [[European]] [[rodent]]s of the family [[Gliridae]]; also called ''[[Myoxidae]]'' or ''{{taxlink|Muscardinidae|family}}'' by some taxonomists.
# {{context|UK|lang=en}} {{taxlink|Muscardinus avellanarius|species}}, the [[hazel dormouse]].
# {{context|figuratively|lang=en}} A person who sleeps a great deal, or who falls asleep readily (by analogy with the sound hibernation of the dormouse).

